    ],
    "solution": "<p><img src=\"https://app-content.fly-assets.uk/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mohamneu/c7a0cfde-eec0-437e-aea9-008f3525a581/7ce90a60-4245-11f1-a7dd-e720d6840823/file-jaoe38c1mohamnev.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.fly-assets.uk/image/jaoe38c1mohamneu/c7a0cfde-eec0-437e-aea9-008f3525a581/7ce90a60-4245-11f1-a7dd-e720d6840823/file-jaoe38c1mohamnev.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2026 (Online) 5th April Evening Shift Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 4 English Explanation 1\"></p>\n<p>To compare the stability of alkenes, we mainly look at how many alkyl groups are attached to the double bond. More alkyl groups means more hyperconjugation, so the alkene becomes more stable.</p>\n<div></div>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.fly-assets.uk/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mohamo3c/46f6704c-cf01-4bed-9a72-43a88e2b473b/7d6f9f80-4245-11f1-a7dd-e720d6840823/file-jaoe38c1mohamo3d.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.fly-assets.uk/image/jaoe38c1mohamo3c/46f6704c-cf01-4bed-9a72-43a88e2b473b/7d6f9f80-4245-11f1-a7dd-e720d6840823/file-jaoe38c1mohamo3d.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2026 (Online) 5th April Evening Shift Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 4 English Explanation 2\"></p><div></div><img src=\"https://app-content.fly-assets.uk/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mohamoqd/43339f15-07a9-41ea-bc94-84db6e6c2062/7dee1e50-4245-11f1-a7dd-e720d6840823/file-jaoe38c1mohamoqe.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.fly-assets.uk/image/jaoe38c1mohamoqd/43339f15-07a9-41ea-bc94-84db6e6c2062/7dee1e50-4245-11f1-a7dd-e720d6840823/file-jaoe38c1mohamoqe.png?format=png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2026 (Online) 5th April Evening Shift Chemistry - Hydrocarbons Question 4 English Explanation 3\"><p></p>\n<p>(D) $\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{HC}=\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\quad(3 \\propto-\\mathrm{H})$</p>\n<p>More substituted alkenes are more stable because they have more $\\alpha-H$ atoms. These $\\alpha-H$ atoms take part in hyperconjugation, which stabilizes the double bond.</p>\n<p>Now compare each alkene:</p>\n<p>C. $2,3$-Dimethylbut-$2$-ene is the most substituted (tetra-substituted), so it is the most stable.</p>\n<p>A. $2$-Methylbut-$2$-ene is tri-substituted, so it is next in stability.</p>\n<p>B. cis-But-$2$-ene is di-substituted, so it is less stable than A.</p>\n<p>D. Prop-$1$-ene is mono-substituted, so it is the least stable.</p>\n<p>Order: $\\quad C&gt;A&gt;B&gt;D$.</p>",
